  <h1 class="hidetitle">Modeling Version Requirements in Open Source Packaging</h1>
  <h2>A universal model for understanding and describing requirements</h2>
  <h3>Josie Anugerah, Caleb Brown, Elitsa Bankova, Eve Martin-Jones, and Nicky Ringland</h3>
  <p>Open source dependencies – reusable code libraries with an open source license – are employed in almost all software projects. About 96 percent of commercial codebases contain open source software, and 70 to 90 percent of any given software code is open source licensed, according to <a href="https://www.linuxfoundation.org/blog/blog/a-summary-of-census-ii-open-source-software-application-libraries-the-world-depends-on">a recent Linux Foundation report</a>.</p>
  <p>As open source dependency use has grown, concerns have emerged about whether we can effectively manage the risks of these third-party packages. Malicious packages continue to be published, yet consumption practices lag behind with developers frequently downloading versions known to be malicious. For example, a <a href="https://www.sonatype.com/state-of-the-software-supply-chain">2024 report from Sonatype</a> states that three years after the Log4Shell exposure, 13 percent of current Log4j downloads are of vulnerable versions. Moreover, 80 percent of open source dependencies are left un-upgraded for more than a year, even though 95 percent of them have safer alternatives. These trends raise doubts about whether the tools and mechanisms for managing open source packages are well understood and effectively used.</p>
  <p>This article focuses on clarifying one fundamental package-management mechanism: requirements. For a given open source dependency in a project, the requirement defines which versions of that dependency are acceptable. While the concept of requirements is the same across packaging ecosystems (such as npm, PyPI, and RubyGems), the syntax used to represent them is not, creating unnecessary confusion. These differences make it seem as though requirements of different ecosystems express different ideas, when in fact they describe the same underlying principles.</p>
  <p>This confusion limits the development of cross-ecosystem tooling for managing open source packages. Most tools are tied to a single ecosystem, despite multilanguage repositories being common. As a result, tools for problems such as vulnerability management are fragmented, duplicating effort and producing inconsistent results. In theory, one tool could handle dependencies across ecosystems, but few such tools exist.</p>
  <p>Although there is a de facto standard for version specification (Semantic Versioning 2.0.0, or SemVer 2.0), there is no corresponding standard for specifying requirements. It is infeasible to unify the current requirement specification syntax across systems, but defining what they mean in a rigorous way can help.</p>
  <p>We propose a universal model of requirement actions. The model does not provide a new syntax for adoption but offers a precise way for ecosystems to define the meaning of their requirement operators. With this shared understanding, we can build more effective tools for managing dependencies.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Definitions</h3>
  <p>An open source software <i>package</i> is a unit of code distributed for open source consumption. The intention is to save developer resources by reusing code that is already well tested and used. When a package is imported for use within a piece of software, it becomes a <i>dependency</i> of that software. A dependency may, in turn, have dependencies of its own, transitively; these are called the package’s <i>indirect</i> dependencies.</p>
  <p>A package may be <i>versioned</i> according to <a href="https://semver.org/">SemVer 2.0</a>. For the purpose of this discussion, versions are assumed to be specified strictly by SemVer 2.0. Build metadata and prereleases can be ignored while focusing on the major, minor, and patch numbering scheme without loss of generality for the purposes of the requirements model.</p>
  <p>A <i>requirement</i> is a constraint placed on a project’s dependency to limit which versions are to be used—for example, to guarantee a feature is available or to avoid known defective versions. The set of <i>allowable versions</i> is determined by applying a requirement to the set of available package versions.</p>
  <p>The process of <i>dependency resolution</i> chooses an extant version for each package from the set of allowable versions. Each <i>dependency resolution tool</i> (pip, yarn, npm, etc.) is an implementation of dependency resolution. The dependency resolution algorithm differs among tools, but the operations they perform are all related.</p>
  <p>Open source packaging <i>ecosystems</i> (or <i>systems</i>) such as PyPI, Maven, npm, and others adhere to the broad strokes of SemVer 2.0 when labeling their versions, though the semantics can be difficult to enforce. (What exactly is a “<i>breaking change,”</i> for example? <a href="https://www.hyrumslaw.com/">Hyrum’s law</a> shows that almost any change breaks something.)</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>The Version Space</h3>
  <p>The space of all package versions available in a given ecosystem is called the version space. It has a total ordering (with the exception of build parts), as defined by SemVer 2.0. A total ordering means that, given any two versions in the space, one version must be equal to, less than, or greater than the other. This ordering is unrelated to the date on which these versions were published or updated. Version <code>2.0.0</code> may have been published two years ago and <code>1.3.4</code> published today, but <code>1.3.4</code> will always precede <code>2.0.0</code> in the total ordering defined by SemVer 2.0.</p>
  <p>Ecosystems often introduce quirks beyond SemVer 2.0 such as <a href="https://www.sonatype.com/state-of-the-software-supply-chain">epochs</a>, <a href="https://www.sonatype.com/state-of-the-software-supply-chain">revision parts</a>, and non-ASCII characters. The requirements model proposed here, however, functions as long as versions are totally ordered, regardless of these variations.</p>
  <p>The version space starts at zero and has no end. There is no version before zero, but there is an infinite possibility of versions after zero.</p>
  <p>Moreover, there are arbitrarily many possible versions between <code>1.0.0</code> and <code>2.0.0</code>, but there is a strict boundary between major version <code>1</code> and major version <code>2</code> (and <code>3</code> and <code>4,</code> and so on). There are also arbitrarily many versions between minor version <code>1.0</code> and <code>1.1,</code> and so on. In other words, the version space is actually an infinite space of disjoint spaces. Despite this complexity, there is still a total order of versions for each version space, as defined by SemVer 2.0.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>The Requirements Model</h3>
  <p>A <i>requirement</i> is a pattern that specifies a subspace of the version space. The process of requirement resolution can generate arbitrarily complex subspaces of versions, and for some packaging systems the result cannot be expressed in the requirement notation of the ecosystem. For example, resolution might lead to two versions, <code>1.0.0</code> and <code>3.0.0</code>, both satisfying the constraints, even if the underlying language has no syntax for selecting either of two explicit versions.</p>
  <p>In order to express such situations, we define our own notation that can capture these complex subspaces. We stress we are not proposing a user-facing syntax but a notation that defines the meaning of that syntax and its results.</p>
  <h4>The model</h4>
  <p>Our model has an interval notation, using closed and open intervals, which are used to describe which extant versions satisfy the requirements. The total ordering defined by SemVer 2.0 makes the meaning of an interval unambiguous.</p>
  <p>The traditional form of a square bracket specifies a closed interval, and a parenthesis specifies an open interval. The interval may have one version, such as</p>
  <p><code>[1.0.0]</code></p>
  <p>to specify the single version <code>1.0.0</code>; or two versions, as in</p>
  <p><code>[1.0.0,2.0.0)</code></p>
  <p>to specify the subspace that starts with version <code>1.0.0</code> and, using SemVer 2.0’s ordering rules, includes every version up to but excluding <code>2.0.0</code>. The ordering of versions is always from low to high, so</p>
  <p><code>(2.0.0,1.0.0]</code></p>
  <p>is the empty interval.</p>
  <p>As an example of how this model can express an existing package’s requirements, the npm notation <code>=1.0.0</code> becomes <code>[1.0.0]</code> in our notation, while in Cargo, that same expression is a synonym for <code>^1.0.0</code> that becomes the interval <code>[1.0.0,2.0.0)</code>.</p>
  <p>Intervals alone are not sufficient, though, as sometimes the requirement specification itself or the decisions made during requirement resolution can generate more than one interval. We therefore need a way to define a list of intervals, which we can consider informally to be a unioning operation, as in</p>
  <p><code>[1.0.0] ∪ [2.0.0]</code></p>
  <p>to specify exactly these two versions and no other. This corresponds to the <code>||</code> operator in npm, or the <code>,</code> (comma) operator in Maven and NuGet, although many other packaging ecosystems have no equivalent.</p>
  <p>Analogously, we can add the set-like operations of intersection and exclusion, as in</p>
  <p><code>[1.0.0,3.0.0) ∩ [2.0.0,4.0.0)</code></p>
  <p>to specify the intersection of two intervals, and</p>
  <p><code>[1.0.0,2.0.0) - [1.5.0]</code></p>
  <p>to exclude the version <code>1.5.0</code> from the space of allowed versions with major version <code>1</code>.</p>
  <p>For completeness, intersection and exclusion operators are not strictly required to specify the version subspaces—intervals with the union operator can express these subspaces without intersection and exclusion—but the operations they provide arise often during requirement resolution, so the shorthand they provide can be convenient.</p>
  <p>Also, for convenience, we introduce a maximum value for a field, <code>∞</code>, to allow us to convert open intervals to closed ones at the boundary. That is,</p>
  <p><code>[1.0.0,2.0.0)</code></p>
  <p>can also be expressed as</p>
  <p><code>[1.0.0,1.∞.∞]</code></p>
  <p>(The minimum value of a numeric or prerelease field can always be written as a numeral zero.)</p>
  <p>As long as there is a total ordering on the versions in a version space, this model is able to express any constraint defined by a requirement from any ecosystem. Table 1 illustrates how various ecosystem-defined operators can be rewritten as intervals and the union between intervals.</p> 
