  <h4>Which versions are included in an interval?</h4> 
  <p>There are a few real-world considerations to address. First, the interval notation does not define the order of versions; that is done by the ecosystems themselves, usually the same as SemVer 2.0 or an expansion thereof. For example, whether <code>[1.0.0, 1.1.0)</code> includes the prerelease versions such as <code>1.0.0-pre</code> is defined by the rules of the system, not by the model we are providing. To put it another way, the precise set of tagged versions included in the interval <code>[1.0.0,1.∞.∞]</code> depends on the ecosystem in which it is being evaluated. Similarly, the zeroth version is also defined by the ecosystem. While we’ve been focusing on the major, minor, patch notation from SemVer 2.0, this model works for any versioning syntax that has a total ordering of versions.</p>
  <p>Furthermore, the requirement alone does not yield a concrete set of allowable versions. The requirement must be applied to some ordered set of available versions to produce a concrete set of allowable versions. For example, we cannot know which versions are allowable from the requirement <code>[1.0.0, 1.1.0)</code> alone. We need to know what the set of available versions are (say, <code>1.0.0, 1.0.1, 2.0.0</code>) so we can use the requirement to constrain this set to the allowable versions (<code>1.0.0, 1.0.1</code>).</p>
  <p>In some systems, requirements apply to the set of all versions of a package. In others, they apply to more specific sets that take into account variables such as the operating system and architecture. For example, in PyPI, a package might offer different sets of versions for Windows x86-64 and macOS ARM64. Depending on the machine and architecture where the dependency resolution tool is running, the relevant requirement is applied to one set of versions or the other. The requirements model itself works the same way, regardless of how the available version set is defined.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h4>This model allows ecosystems to precisely define their requirement syntax</h4>
  <p>Each ecosystem has its own requirement syntax. Ecosystems such as npm use algebraic operators (<code>&lt;</code>, <code>&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;=</code>, <code>&gt;=</code>), while in Go, the operator is implicit, so a requirement <code>1.0.0</code> means <code>[1.0.0,∞.∞.∞)</code>.</p>
  <p>In fact, the same notation in different ecosystems might have different meanings. The requirement <code>1.0.0</code> might mean exactly the version <code>1.0.0</code> (npm, RubyGems), it might mean any version with major version <code>1</code> (Cargo), or it might mean any version with major version at least <code>1</code> (NuGet).</p>
  <p>Instead of proposing another syntax for adoption, the intention for our model is to provide the ability to define such ecosystem-specific syntaxes precisely. Table 2 demonstrates how the model expresses each of the meanings of <code>1.0.0</code> across various ecosystems.</p>
