  <p>In practice, the meaning of a system’s requirement operators is not usually well defined through its documentation. Descriptions tend to be informal and do not completely define the behavior. Describing the behavior of a system’s requirement operators in terms of the model might help in having a shared understanding of what requirements are, what various operators do, and how dependency resolution is implemented.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h4>The model is complete</h4>
  <p>The model is able to express an arbitrarily complex subspace of the version space. Most ecosystem-specific syntaxes are not complete in this sense. This matters because during the implementation of requirement resolution, intermediate results may be arbitrarily complex.</p>
  <p>To illustrate, suppose we want to debug a diamond dependency conflict as depicted in Figure 1. The version <code>0</code> denotes the zeroth version.</p>
  <img src="https://spawn-queue.acm.org/cms/attachment/html/10.1145/3786612/assets/html/3786612_fig01.jpg" alt="Figure 1. 
An example of the diamond dependency problem
" />
  <br />Figure 1. An example of the diamond dependency problem
  <p>Many ecosystems are unable to express the resolved requirement on package <code>B</code>. In a resolution algorithm that tries to satisfy all the requirements imposed on a package, the resulting requirement for package <code>B</code> is</p>
  <p><code>[3.0.0, ∞.∞.∞) ∩ [0, 2.0.0)</code></p>
  <p>Many ecosystems lack the intersection operator. While some are able to express the empty set, this simplication doesn’t provide the specific requirements necessary to understand the conflict.</p>
  <p>Consider also the exclusion of a version from a range. Suppose we want to allow any version <code>[1.0.0, 2.0.0)</code> but want to exclude <code>1.0.2</code>, as it is vulnerable. This can be written using the exclusion operator as</p>
  <p><code>[1.0.0, 2.0.0) - 1.0.2</code></p>
  <p>This representation adapts to a changing set of available versions. Given the set of available versions <code>1.0.0</code>, <code>1.0.2</code>, <code>1.0.3</code>, <code>1.0.4</code>, however, this could also be written as</p>
  <p><code>[1.0.0] ∪ [1.0.3, 2.0.0)</code></p>
  <p>The latter representation is useful for debugging a version upgrade or a requirements conflict at a given point in time. If new versions are published, however, this representation may become out of date. If version <code>1.0.1</code> were to be published, this requirement would need to be updated to be</p>
  <p><code>[1.0.0, 1.0.1] ∪ [1.0.3, 2.0.0)</code></p>
  <p>These representations are not possible in many ecosystems. Some don’t have an exclusion operator, others don’t have a union operator, and still others don’t have either operator. Details about which ecosystems support the intersection, union, and exclusion operators can be found in Table 1.</p>
  <p>These examples are deliberately small and involve few requirements, but real-world requirements are far more complicated. A popular package may be imported from many places within a dependency graph, and a project typically doesn’t have one or two but tens, hundreds, or even thousands of dependencies. Vulnerability remediation tools (such as <a href="https://osv.dev/blog/posts/announcing-guided-remediation-in-osv-scanner/">OSV-Scanner’s guided remediation feature</a>) often require the ability to describe complex resolved requirements.</p>
  <p>As such, it is important to be able to reason about requirements precisely at scale, and the requirements model provides a rigorous way to do so.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h4>The model provides an abstraction for requirements</h4>
  <p>Existing requirement syntaxes are coupled to the system’s resolution algorithm and to the dependency management strategy of the user. This needn’t be the case.</p>
  <p>For example, consider the Go ecosystem (Table 3). Since the <code>go</code> tool always selects the lowest available version (<a href="https://research.swtch.com/vgo-mvs">Minimum Version Selection</a>), the requirement syntax is kept deliberately simple (and therefore limited) to match. Users manage dependencies mainly by reviewing new versions and updating their pinned requirements. In Go, the requirement syntax, dependency resolver, and update process all work as a single, connected system.</p>
