  <p>Dependency management works differently in npm, where dependencies are typically managed by using the caret (<code>^</code>) operator for most requirements. If no other flags are specified, <code>npm install &lt;package&gt;</code> defaults to the <code>^</code> requirement. (See <a href="https://blog.deps.dev/after-the-advisory/">https://blog.deps.dev/after-the-advisory/</a> for an analysis of how prevalent the <code>^</code> operator is in npm and how this affects vulnerability management.) The caret operator, combined with <code>npm install/upgrade</code> selecting the highest available version, lets users upgrade without introducing breaking changes. By contrast, the Go ecosystem has no equivalent caret operator, because rather than selecting the highest available versions, it selects the minimum available version.</p>
  <p>The requirement syntax, dependency resolution tools and dependency management strategies are all coupled together, but there is no reason why they need to be. Versioning is, for the most part, system-agnostic, because systems adhere to the broad strokes of SemVer 2.0. Requirement syntaxes and dependency-resolution tools, however, have grown to be system-specific. Each system is solving the same problem, and we should be able to choose a dependency management strategy independent of the language.</p>
  <p>The requirements model proposed here provides a fully expressive abstraction between the requirement syntax and anything that depends on it, so requirements can be decoupled from things such as dependency management strategies and dependency resolution tools.</p>
  <p>In fact, because all ecosystem-specific requirements can be translated into the model, it should be possible to write a single tool for resolution or vulnerability remediation instead of having ecosystem-specific implementations. This prevents work from being repeated to develop tooling and provides consistent results. Thinking this way, we can apply learnings or strategies from one ecosystem to another and have more cross-ecosystem collaboration. To this end, we have published an open source library at <a href="https://github.com/google/deps.dev">https://github.com/google/deps.dev</a> that parses requirements from eight ecosystems and translates them into the model.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Dependency Resolution</h3>
  <p>Requirement resolution doesn’t yet leave us with a dependency resolution result where a version is chosen for each dependency package.</p>
  <p>As mentioned earlier, <i>dependency resolution</i> chooses an extant version for each package from the allowable versions provided by applying requirements to the set of available versions. Dependency resolution must consider all versions of all dependencies, direct and indirect. (Despite common misconception, lock files of dependencies aren’t used in the resolution process.) This makes resolution more complex than it may first appear.</p>
  <p>For example, the diamond dependency problem is solved in different ways across different systems. Systems such as npm allow for multiple versions to be installed so there are enough packages to satisfy every requirement. Other systems such as PyPI require only one package to be installed, so the requirements conflict will result in an error.</p>
  <p>Dependency resolution involves more than requirements, however. Even if requirements stay the same, the live version set changes as new versions are published, old ones are removed, or patches are released—so results can differ day to day. Resolution also accounts for factors like architecture-specific dependencies and system cache. The inputs to dependency resolution are many, making the result difficult to pin down. (For more details on these, see the <i>acmqueue</i> article, “<a href="https://queue.acm.org/detail.cfm?id=3723000">The Surprise of Multiple Dependency Graphs</a>.”)</p>
  <p>We should aim for clarity in the dependency resolution process, and dependency resolution relies on requirements. The model is a step toward precisely defining requirements and how they function, but there is much more to dependency resolution than requirements.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Conclusion</h3>
  <p>Requirements define which versions of packages we import into our projects. While SemVer 2.0 provides a shared understanding of version specification, no such equivalent specification exists for requirements. The tooling for managing dependencies is system-specific, as is the requirement syntax. This leads to duplicate work and inconsistent results.</p>
  <p>Starting with a shared syntax might once have been possible, but there are now many different accepted notations for specifying requirements. While not proposing that all ecosystems adopt the syntax of the requirements model, we offer this model to provide an abstraction. All ecosystem-specific requirements can be translated into the model as well as being defined within it, and dependency-resolution tools need not be specific to a requirement syntax.</p>
  <p>With this model, we hope to see further cross-ecosystem collaboration, better documentation, shared tooling, and, ultimately, better dependency management.</p>
